                                                                                                               Ministers jaunts cost Rs 19.2 lakh
          OUR SPECIAL CORRESPONDENT                           Naveen Patnaik: Going nowhere                                  
	Bhubaneswar, July 22: While chief minister Naveen Patnaik stayed put in his state and avoided any travel to foreign destinations in this past nine years, eight of his ministerial colleagues made foreign trips.         
	Prior to his political life that begun in 1997, Naveen had travelled widely.        
	According to the information provided by the parliamentary affairs minister, Raghunath Mohanty, to the Assembly today, it seems that Naveens colleagues more than made up for the trips that Naveen did not make.         
	In this period cabinet ministers travelled to the USA, England, France, Australia, Italy, Israel, Egypt, South Africa, Iran, Malaysia, Indonesia, Singapore and Thailand incurring an expenditure of Rs 19.2 lakh out of the state exchequer on their foreign jaunt. Department for International Development (DFID-UK) and UNDP bore the expenses of two such travels to South Africa and the two Southeast Asian countries.         
	Finance minister Prafulla Chandra Ghadei travelled to Australia and Singapore in May 2007 on an official visit and the state exchequer bore an expense to the tune of Rs 4.25 lakh. While former law minister Biswa Bhusan Harichandan travelled to London, Zurich, Geneva and Vienna in April 2007 to attend conferences and incurred an expenditure of Rs 2.63 lakh.         
	Similarly, the former agriculture minister, Surendra Nath Nayak, visited Israel and Egypt in May 2006 at a cost of Rs 1.13 lakh to study the countries agriculture system.        
	A month later, he went to South Africa sponsored by the UK governments DFID.         
	The then energy minister, Surya Narayan Patro, travelled to Thailand in August 2005 and to London in November in the same year. Next June, he travelled to the USA on another official trip. The aggregate travel bill was Rs 5.22 lakh.        
	During June 2006, the then commerce and transport minister, Jaynarayan Mishra, had visited London, Paris and Geneva, on an official trip at an expense of Rs 2.38 lakh borne from the state exchequer.         
	The then steel and mines minister, Padmanav Behera, too, travelled to Teheran in November 2005, incurring an expenditure of Rs 2.12 lakh.         
	Tourism minister Debi Prasad Mishra went to Indonesia in September 2007 and Italy and France in May-June last year. His travel bill was Rs 1.97 lakh.         
	Finally, former textile minister Golak Bihari Nayak went to Malaysia in June-July, 2007 incurring an expenditure of Rs 60,925. Earlier, he had travelled to Malaysia and Thailand in December 2006 on an UNDP-sponsored trip.                                                                                                                                                                           
